<h2>New York Incentives & Rebates</h2>
<p>New York offers some of the most generous solar incentives in the United States, making solar installation highly attractive for homeowners. The federal solar Investment Tax Credit (ITC) provides a 30% tax credit for solar installations through 2032, then steps down to 26% in 2033 and 22% in 2034. This credit applies to the total system cost, including equipment, installation, and permitting fees, and can be carried forward if it exceeds tax liability in the installation year.</p>

<p>The NY-Sun Initiative, New York's flagship solar incentive program, provides additional rebates for solar installations. As of 2024, residential rebates range from \$0.40 to \$1.00 per watt depending on system size and location, with higher incentives available in certain utility territories. ConEd customers can receive additional rebates through utility-specific programs, with some areas eligible for combined incentives exceeding \$1.50 per watt. The NY-Sun program also offers performance-based incentives for larger systems, providing ongoing payments based on actual solar production.</p>

<p>For HVAC systems, New York provides rebates through the Clean Heat Statewide program, offering up to \$10,000 for heat pump installations in eligible areas. ConEd customers can access additional rebates of \$500-2,500 for high-efficiency HVAC equipment through the Energy Efficiency Programs. The state also offers financing options through the Green Jobs-Green New York program, providing low-interest loans for energy efficiency improvements. Property tax exemptions are available for solar installations, ensuring that system additions don't increase property tax assessments for 15 years.</p>

<p>Net metering policies in New York are particularly favorable, with investor-owned utilities required to provide full retail credit for excess solar production. The Value of Distributed Energy Resources (VDER) program provides additional compensation for solar production during peak demand periods, further improving the economics of solar installations. Low-to-moderate income households can access additional incentives through programs like the Affordable Solar program, which provides enhanced rebates and financing options.</p>

